       âˆ_i A_i     âŸ¶  âˆ_{i,j} Ï_{U_i, U_iâˆ©U_j}(A_i) Ã— Ï_{U_j, U_iâˆ©U_j}(A_j)
   ```
   Here:
   Â· âˆ_i A_i is the product object representing the uncoupled collection of all local agents.
   Â· The two parallel morphisms Î±, Î²: âˆ_i A_i â†’ âˆ_{i,j} Ï_{...}(A_i) Ã— Ï_{...}(A_j) are defined by projecting to the first and second factor for each (i,j), respectively.
   Â· The compatibility condition is precisely the statement that Î± âˆ˜ Î¹_A = Î² âˆ˜ Î¹_A, where Î¹_A is the canonical map from the co-cone.
2. Apply the Sheaf Axiom. By definition, a sheaf ğ’® is a functor that turns colimits in the site (X, J) into limits in Cog. The covering {U_i â†’ U} generates a colimit cocone in the category of presheaves. The sheaf condition for ğ’® states that the canonical map is an isomorphism:
   ```
       ğ’®(U) â†’ Eq( âˆ_i ğ’®(U_i) â‡‰ âˆ_{i,j} ğ’®(U_i âˆ© U_j) )
   ```
   The equalizer Eq(...) is the limit of the diagram âˆ_i ğ’®(U_i) â‡‰ âˆ_{i,j} ğ’®(U_i âˆ© U_j).
3. Universal Property Yields Synthesis. The compatible family {A_i} defines a morphism from the terminal object 1 into the equalizer Eq(âˆ_i ğ’®(U_i) â‡‰ âˆ_{i,j} ğ’®(U_i âˆ© U_j)). Since ğ’®(U) is isomorphic to this equalizer, there exists a unique morphism (up to unique isomorphism) È·: 1 â†’ ğ’®(U) corresponding to a global section A_U. This A_U is the required synthesized agent. Its uniqueness up to isomorphism guarantees it is a well-defined synthesis of the local A_i. The "novelty" arises from the fact that A_U is an object in ğ’®(U), a domain of greater complexity than any individual U_i; its internal structure (its relationships to other objects and its endomorphisms in Cog) is generated by the universal construction and is not merely a coproduct of the A_i. âˆ

