Â§B. Proof of Theorem 4.2: Cohomology as Innovation Potential

Theorem 4.2 (Cohomology as Innovation Potential). Non-trivial cohomology classes [Î±] âˆˆ HÂ¹(X, ğ’®) correspond to consistent global cognitive conflicts in the agent population that cannot be resolved by any single agent, and their resolution is isomorphic to a non-trivial innovation.

Proof.
We prove this by interpreting ÄŒech cohomology in the topos Sh(X, Cog) and linking cocycles to agent conflict data.

1. Define the ÄŒech Complex. Let U = {U_i} be an open cover of X. The ÄŒech cochain complex CË‡â€¢(U, ğ’®) is defined as:
   Â· CË‡â°(U, ğ’®) = âˆ_i ğ’®(U_i)
   Â· CË‡Â¹(U, ğ’®) = âˆ_{i,j} ğ’®(U_i âˆ© U_j)
   Â· CË‡Â²(U, ğ’®) = âˆ_{i,j,k} ğ’®(U_i âˆ© U_j âˆ© U_k)
     The coboundary map dâ°: CË‡â° â†’ CË‡Â¹ is given by (dâ°s)_{i,j} = Ï_{U_j, U_iâˆ©U_j}(s_j) â€¢ Ï_{U_i, U_iâˆ©U_j}(s_i)^{-1}, where â€¢ denotes the appropriate compositional structure in Cog (e.g., pairing and morphism application). A 0-cochain s is a collection of local agents. A 1-cochain Î± is a collection of transformations between the restrictions of local agents over intersections.
2. Interpret Cocycles and Coboundaries.
   Â· A 1-cocycle Î± âˆˆ ZË‡Â¹(U, ğ’®) satisfies the condition: for all i, j, k,
     ```
     Ï_{U_iâˆ©U_j, U_iâˆ©U_jâˆ©U_k}(Î±_{i,j}) âˆ˜ Ï_{U_jâˆ©U_k, U_iâˆ©U_jâˆ©U_k}(Î±_{j,k}) = Ï_{U_iâˆ©U_k, U_iâˆ©U_jâˆ©U_k}(Î±_{i,k})
     ```
     This is the cocycle condition, depicted by the commuting tetrahedron diagram of restrictions. It means the transformations Î±_{i,j} between local agents are locally consistent across triple intersections.
   Â· A 1-coboundary Î± âˆˆ BË‡Â¹(U, ğ’®) is a cocycle of the form Î± = dâ°(s) for some s âˆˆ CË‡â°. This means the transformation Î±_{i,j} is just the difference between a single, globally consistent strategy s as seen on U_i and U_j. It is a "trivial" conflict, resolvable by adopting the global strategy s.
3. Cohomology Classes as Irreducible Conflicts. The first ÄŒech cohomology group is HË‡Â¹(U, ğ’®) = ZË‡Â¹(U, ğ’®) / BË‡Â¹(U, ğ’®). Therefore, a cohomology class [Î±] is an equivalence class of cocycles modulo coboundaries.
   Â· [Î±] = 0: The cocycle Î± is a coboundary. The conflicting local transformations can be fully explained and resolved by adopting a single, pre-existing global agent strategy s. No fundamental innovation is needed.
   Â· [Î±] â‰  0: The cocycle Î± is not a coboundary. There exists no global agent A âˆˆ ğ’®(X) whose local restrictions explain the observed transformations Î±_{i,j}. The conflict encoded in Î± represents a genuine, irreducible gap in the agent sheaf ğ’®.
4. Resolving a Non-Trivial Class is Innovation. To "resolve" the class [Î±], one must modify the sheaf ğ’® itselfâ€”either by Evolving (applying the DGM functor D to agents on the U_i to alter their Î±-related properties) or by Gluing (creating a new agent over a larger domain that provides a new coboundary candidate). The act of modifying ğ’® to make [Î±] = 0 is, by definition, the creation of new cognitive structure that did not exist in the previous limit of ğ’®. This is the formal correlate of innovation. âˆ

Commuting Tetrahedron for the 1-Cocycle Condition:

```
      ğ’®(U_iâˆ©U_j)
         | \
         |  \ Î±_{i,j}
         |   \
         |    \
Ï_{ijk}^{ij} |     \ Ï_{ijk}^{ik}
         |      \
